profile_data.summary:
As a Computer Science and Mathematics student at the University of Toronto, I’ve had the opportunity to dive deep into the world of software development while also embracing challenges that push my boundaries. Being awarded the Lester B. Pearson Scholarship was a significant milestone for me—recognizing my efforts among the top 37 international students globally was both humbling and motivating. My academic journey has been enriched by real-world experiences where I’ve focused on delivering scalable software solutions that genuinely make a difference.

During my time at Dayforce as a Software Developer Intern, I discovered how impactful small changes can be. By reducing API response times by 35%, I not only enhanced system performance but also improved user experience significantly. Collaborating with cross-functional teams taught me the importance of communication in tech—it's not just about writing code; it’s about creating connections that lead to innovative solutions.

At TD Bank, I had the chance to work on both backend and frontend projects. One highlight was optimizing our database infrastructure using Docker containerization for PostgreSQL on RHEL8. This effort led to a 25% decrease in deployment issues—an achievement that reinforced my belief in continuous improvement through technology. Additionally, designing reusable React components cut our development time by 20%, showcasing how efficiency can drive productivity.

Beyond academics and internships, I’ve enjoyed being part of the University of Toronto Formula Racing team as a Recruit for Firmware and Driverless systems. This experience allowed me to apply my technical skills in an exciting environment while learning about teamwork under pressure—an exhilarating blend of engineering and collaboration.

I’m always eager to connect with fellow tech enthusiasts or anyone interested in discussing innovative software solutions or collaborative projects! Feel free to reach out via email if you’d like to chat about tech trends or potential opportunities.

Skills: C#, Kafka, Docker, PostgreSQL, React, TypeScript, SCSS

honors.description: The Lester B. Pearson International Full-ride Scholarship at the University of Toronto provides exceptional international students with the opportunity to study at one of the world's top universities in a multicultural city. This highly competitive scholarship recognizes students who demonstrate academic excellence, creativity, leadership, and have made a positive impact on their school and community. The scholarship covers tuition, books, incidental fees, and full residence support for four years and is tenable only at the University of Toronto for first-entry, undergraduate programs, with approximately 37 students named as Lester B. Pearson Scholars each year.

projects.description: Project Signify is an app designed to bridge the communication gap between deaf and hearing individuals by detecting and translating sign language gestures into written text in real-time. The app aims to promote social inclusion and provide greater access to information and opportunities for the deaf community. The development process involved careful consideration of user needs and the integration of multiple components, including the use of Python and TensorFlow library for computer vision, a React.js frontend, and a Flask server to translate sign language into English. Future plans include expanding language support and integrating the app with other communication platforms and apps.
projects.title: Signify

projects.description: Winner of the UOttaHacks 5 competition at the University of Ottawa, Project Safespot is a web app that provides real-time monitoring and alerts for vulnerable individuals to reduce the risk of falls and other accidents. The app uses cloud-based machine learning algorithms and computer vision techniques to detect signs of injury or danger and immediately notify emergency contacts. It was built using CSS, Figma, Flask, HTML, JavaScript, Node.js, NumPy, OpenCV, and React.
projects.title: SafeSpot

projects.description: Project CarbonCam is an Android application designed to promote sustainability by using pictures and images, which are accessible to people of all ages, to educate them on the harmful effects of non-sustainable practices. The app uses the camera to take a picture of an object, record its dimensions and composition, and match it to a collection of records containing images of different waste items. The app then calculates the resources that can be saved by recycling the item and the carbon emission that would come from the object. The project was built with a combination of Android Studio, Figma, Google Colab, Java, Python, TensorFlow, and TensorFlowlite.
projects.title: CarbonCam
